i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iOn the modern Internet, most websites already support HTTPS. The		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iSSL/TLS encryption protocol will encrypt user's request and the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iwebsite's response, so that malicious users along the way cannot steal		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ior tamper with the information. One important component of SSL/TLS		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iprotocol is asymmetric cryptographic algorithms. For these algorithms,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ithe key is separated into a **public key** and a **private key**, with		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ithe public key being public and the private key being protected		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
icarefully.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iAccessing a HTTPS website usually follows these procedures:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i1. The website sends its **public key** (as a certificate) to the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   browser.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i2. The browser will verify the public key, in case that a		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   man-in-the-middle modified the key in order to block or tap into		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   the communication.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   - The browser (or the operating system) has a list of credible		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     Certificate Authorities (CA) builtin, and they can verify		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     cryptographically that the public key is generated by one of		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     them.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     - The CA will use various measures (multiple levels of		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i       certificate chain, physically isolated key storage device) to		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i       protect their own private key, so that no one can steal their		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i       private key and generate trusted certificates at will.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   - The browser will contact a server from the CA to lookup the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     Certificate Revocation List. The List stores all certificates		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     that are indeed generated by the CA, but cannot be trusted		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     anymore due to a system error/private key leak.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i3. After verifying the public key, the browser generates a **random		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   key** locally for this connection.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i4. The browser encrypts the random key with the website's public key,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   and sends it to the website server.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   - The encrypted data can only be decrypted with the website's		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     private key, not with the public key, so a man-in-the-middle		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     cannot obtain the random key.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i5. The website server decrypts the content with the locally stored		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   **private key** to obtain the browser-generated random key.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i6. The browser and website server start to talk using the random key		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   with **symmetric encryption**, where both parties use the same key		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   to encrypt or decrypt, such as AES.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   - Asymmetric encryption is no longer used since it's		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     computationally more expensive, while symmetric encryption		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     provides better performance.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iAsymmetric encryption guarantees the security of exchanging symmetric		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ikeys between the browser and website server, and ensures that the data		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iis not stolen or tampered with.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iBut with the birth of quantum computers, there comes a slight change.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iWith a quantum computer that is "powerful enough", or having enough		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
inumber of "qubits" (quantum bits),		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i[Shor's Algorithm](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shor%27s_algorithm)		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ithat runs on quantum computers can efficiently crack traditional		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iasymmetric encryption algorithms including RSA and ECDSA, which are		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ibased on the difficulty on decomposing prime factors.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iYet with the heat on quantum computing, quantum computers evolve		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
irapidly. The most powerful quantum computer made public to this day is		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iIBM's 53 qubit computer (See		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i[Quantum Supremacy on Wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quantum_supremacy)),		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
istill not enough for cracking RSA or ECDSA with Shor's Algorithm, but		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
itechnology developing at high speed may make this possible any time.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iTherefore, cryptographers start to develop asymmetric encryption		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ialgorithms that cannot be efficiently cracked with quantum computers,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iand promote their usage, to prepare for the day when RSA is cracked.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iSince late 2016, the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i[Open Quantum Safe Project](https://openquantumsafe.org/) began		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iintegrating existing quantum-resistant algorithms into their `liboqs`		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ilibrary, and integrate it to popular cryptographic libraries, such as		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iOpenSSL and BoringSSL, to simplify the deployment of new cryptographic		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ialgorithms.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iAt the same time, the project also provides documentation on		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
icompilation and integration of software, including nginx, Chromium,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ietc. Therefore, by making simple modifications according to the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
idocumentation, we can be prepared for the birth of a practical quantum		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
icomputer.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i> WARNING: All post-quantum cryptographic algorithms here are		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i> relatively new, and are		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i> [under the process of NIST standardization](https://csrc.nist.gov/Projects/post-quantum-cryptography/round-3-submissions),		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i> so they may still have undiscovered weaknesses. Although Open		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i> Quantum Safe does provide workarounds to reduce the risk, it's not		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i> recommended to use them in production before their standardization		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i> process is complete.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i## nginx / OpenSSL		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iSince nginx uses OpenSSL or BoringSSL as the cryptographic library,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ithere's no need to make any change on nginx, simply replacing OpenSSL		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iwith the Open Quantum Safe version is enough.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iOpen Quantum Safe		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i[provides a modified Dockerfile that serves as a reference](https://github.com/open-quantum-safe/oqs-demos/tree/master/chromium).		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iReferring to the material above, I also modified my Dockerfile that I		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iuse to compile nginx, to use Open Quantum Safe's OpenSSL.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i[It is available here](https://github.com/xddxdd/dockerfiles/blob/1195fb20a1dfcbcad0fa3c494fe7440841c35963/dockerfiles/nginx/template.Dockerfile).		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iCompared to compiling a normal nginx, there are 2 main changes:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i1. You need to use Open Quantum Safe's OpenSSL, and additionally		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   download and compile `liboqs`, install it to the source code		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   directory of OpenSSL, in order to use it. The related lines in my		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   Dockerfile are 44-52:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   ```bash		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   # Redacted		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   && git clone -b OQS-OpenSSL_1_1_1-stable https://github.com/open-quantum-safe/openssl.git \		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      # Some personal modifications omitted here, they're not necessary for post-quantum cryptography		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   && git clone -b master https://github.com/open-quantum-safe/liboqs.git \		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      && mkdir /tmp/liboqs/build && cd /tmp/liboqs/build \		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      && cmake -DOQS_BUILD_ONLY_LIB=1 -DBUILD_SHARED_LIBS=OFF -DCMAKE_INSTALL_PREFIX=/tmp/openssl/oqs .. \		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      && make -j4 && make install && cd /tmp \		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   # Redacted		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   ```		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   All files are downloaded to `/tmp`. The key is to compile `liboqs`		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   with `cmake`, and install it to the `oqs` subfolder in OpenSSL		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   source code directory.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i2. Additional compilation parameters are needed to include `liboqs` in		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   nginx. At lines 102-104 in my Dockerfile:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   ```bash		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   # Redacted		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   && ./configure \		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      # Redacted some nginx parameters		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      --with-openssl=/tmp/openssl \		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      --with-cc-opt="-I/tmp/openssl/oqs/include" \		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      --with-ld-opt="-L/tmp/openssl/oqs/lib" \		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   && sed -i 's/libcrypto.a/libcrypto.a -loqs/g' objs/Makefile \		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   # Redacted		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   ```		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iAnd proceed to compile nginx normally.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iAfter the compilation and installation is complete, you also need to		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ichange the parameters to use the post-quantum asymmetric cryptographic		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ialgorithms, including **key exchange algorithms** and **identity		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iverification algorithms**:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- **Key exchange algorithms:** used for browsers and websites to		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  exchange symmetric encryption keys.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  Simply change the `ssl_ecdh_curve` parameter in `nginx.conf` to use		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  the elliptic curves of the algorithms, and we're done:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  ```bash		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  ssl_ecdh_curve 'p256_frodo640aes:p256_bike1l1cpa:p256_kyber90s512:p256_ntru_hps2048509:p256_lightsaber:p256_sidhp434:p256_sikep434:prime256v1:secp384r1:secp521r1';		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  ```		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  `nginx -s reload` after making the modifications.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  Here only a fraction of the supported algorithms are enabled, mainly		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  for 2 reasons:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  1. nginx has a limit on the length of the parameter, and will emit		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     an error otherwise;		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  2. The parameters chosen are also supported in the BoringSSL variant		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     of Open Quantum Safe, which is critically important in enabling		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     Chromium support later.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  By the way, the key exchange algorithms all start with `p256_`,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  which means a traditional key exchange algorithm is also used along		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  with post-quantum ones. This is to prevent the case that, the new		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  algorithm has mathmatical loopholes that allow even traditional		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  (Von-Neumann) computers to crack this quickly. By using two key		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  exchange algorithms at the same time, a quantum computer cannot		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  crack them (assuming that the new algorithm works), while if the new		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  algorithm is cracked, the key exchange data is still protected at		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  the level equivalent to traditional key exchange, and won't be		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  cracked immediately by traditional computers.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- **Identity verification algorithms:** used by Certificate		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  Authorities to generate public/private certificates to websites. In		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  order to use these algorithms, you need to either find a CA that		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  supports post-quantum cryptography (doesn't exist yet) to issue you		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  a new cerificate, or generate one by yourself (not trusted by		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  browser). Neither of them works, so I choose not to use it now.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iAfter finishing configuration, you can use the **curl** Docker image		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iprovided by Open Quantum Safe to test your website:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i```bash		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i# Replace the last parameter with desired algorithm, same format as ssl_ecdh_curve		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
idocker run -it openquantumsafe/curl:0.4.0 curl https://lantian.pub --curves p256_frodo640aes		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i```		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i## Chromium / BoringSSL		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iAlthough we have a commandline **curl** to verify it works, a		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ifull-fledged browser's support makes post-quantum cryptography		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ipractical, providing users with better protection. Ope Quantum Safe		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ialso provides a modified BoringSSL, that allows you to experience		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ipost-quantum cryptography on the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i[most popular browser in the world](https://gs.statcounter.com/browser-market-share),		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ionce you compile it into Chromium.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iOpen Quantum Safe also		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i[provides a guide to compile Chromium that is availale here](https://github.com/open-quantum-safe/oqs-demos/tree/master/chromium).		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iCompared to vanilla Chromium, the 4 main differences are:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i1. `git clone https://github.com/open-quantum-safe/boringssl`,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   replacing BoringSSL in `third_party/boringssl/src` in Chromium		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   source code with a modified one.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i2. Download `liboqs`, compile and install to `oqs` directory in		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   BoringSSL source code:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   ```bash		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   git clone --branch master https://github.com/open-quantum-safe/liboqs.git		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   cd liboqs && mkdir build && cd build		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   cmake .. -G"Ninja" -DCMAKE_INSTALL_PREFIX=<CHROMIUM_ROOT>/third_party/boringssl/src/oqs -DOQS_USE_OPENSSL=OFF		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   ninja && ninja install		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   ```		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i3. Patch Chromium with		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   [this modification that uses liboqs](https://github.com/open-quantum-safe/oqs-demos/raw/master/chromium/oqs-mods.patch).		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i4. Run `python2 src/util/generate_build_files.py gn` under folder		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   `third_party/boringssl` to update dependencies, in order to include		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   `liboqs` related content.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iThen proceed to compile Chromium as normal.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iI also modified a Chromium `PKGBUILD` file that Arch Linux users can		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iuse directly. The latest PKGBUILD		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i[is available here](https://github.com/xddxdd/pkgbuild/tree/master/chromium-vaapi-oqs),		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iwhile the version when I wrote this article		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i[is available here (241cfaa)](https://github.com/xddxdd/pkgbuild/tree/241cfaad1d4e0c245efdfb345d9245ef57a07c82/chromium-vaapi-oqs).		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i> Note that compiling Chromium takes a really long time. It took 8		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
